We recommended to the management to do the following courses of action:
The GSO-Designate, with approval of the Municipal Mayor, to submit a request to COA for the immediate and proper disposal of the twelve (12) unserviceable properties of the LGU.
The Municipal Accountant must immediately derecognize the said unserviceable PPE items from the books of accounts of the LGU once proper disposal has been undertaken. She must provide the breakdown of the accumulated depreciation of the “Construction and Heavy Equipment” and “Motor Vehicles” accounts. She must consider them in computing the net book value of every unserviceable asset; Furnish the Office of the Auditor of the certified true copies of the Journal Entry Voucher and other pertinent documentary supports.
The Municipal Accountant must review and trace the entries in the foregoing JEVs pertaining to the three (3) missing equipment in the books of accounts of the LGU and ensure that they are reconciled, recognized and recorded; Prepare adjusting entries if necessary and submit copies of working papers and the like to COA for verification together with the documents requested in No. 4 below.
Aside from the JEVs and copies of transmittal letters, the GSO-Designate must submit more proofs as to the mode of disposal or procedures taken upon disposal of the three (3) missing equipment such as but not limited to:
Certified true copy of the Official Receipts issued by the Municipal Treasurer’s Office at the time of disposal;
File copy of the Public/Auction bidding documents in the disposal of the 3 unserviceable heavy equipment;
If through negotiation, proof of failed public auction/bidding and other documents/records related to the proceedings of the negotiation;
File copy of the Program for disposal and disposal procedures;
File copy of the Attendance Sheets, Minutes of Meetings during the public/auction bidding;
File copy of the images or photos of these items at the time of disposal; and
Other necessary documents that will prove the disposal of these items such as, but not limited to, the COA Appraisal Value.
The GSO-Designate and Municipal Engineer must prepare and maintain property cards of all the construction and heavy equipment and motor vehicles owned by the LGU.
The GSO-Designate must immediately submit the Inventory Report of PPE for CY 2024 to COA for review and verification; Reconcile the physical inventory of construction and heavy equipment and motor vehicles with accounting records and submit working papers and the like to COA for verification.
Henceforth, the GSO-Designate must use the Property Acknowledgment Receipt (PAR), new form, in lieu of the ARE or old form in issuing PPE item to its intended recipient.

We recommended to the management to direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Submit to the Office of the Auditor the supporting documents evidencing receipt of the goods and/or services already recorded as AP;
Effect a reversing journal entry for items recorded as AP without actual receipt of goods and/or services;
Effect a correcting journal entry for items recorded as AP that should have been recorded as ‘Due to Other Funds’ and ‘Due to LGUs’;
Transmit a copy to the Office of the Auditor of the Journal Entry Vouchers for the correction of the erroneous entries together with the working papers and supporting documents; and
Recognize AP for goods and/or services only upon receipt, supported with complete documentation evidencing receipt, of the goods/services, and the appropriate ‘Due to’ accounts for intra- and inter-agency transfers and payables, in conformity with the prescribed Revised Chart of Accounts for LGUs.

We recommended to the management to do the following courses of action:

Require the Municipal Treasurer to stop collecting advance cash payments from barangays for every proposed barangay project;
Require the Municipal Accountant to submit the contracts of service and certificates of acceptance issued by the Punong Barangay of the various projects that comprised the ₱ 3,689,960.00;
Require the Municipal Engineer to ask for Inspection Report from the Barangay Inspectorate Team every time the proposed project of the barangay is already complete and include it as documentary support of the paid disbursement voucher;
Require the Municipal Engineer to render service or complete the proposed project of the barangay first before billing the barangay for the work accomplished and collect payment only after the Punong Barangay issued a Certificate of Project Acceptance;
Require the Municipal Mayor to enter into a contract of service with the concerned Punong Barangay for similar engagements in the future.

We recommended to the management to do the following courses of action:

The Municipal Municipal Treasurer must return the unutilized PDAFs and must immediately issue a check payable to the Bureau of the Treasury amounted to ₱ 123,397.17;
The Municipal Accountant must prepare a corresponding Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to adjust the “Due to Other NGAs” account once the PDAFs are already returned to the Bureau of the Treasury.

We recommended to the management to do the following:

The Kadingilan Water District Supervisor should first ensure that all the water service contracts were duly signed by the Municipal Mayor and the consumers before strictly enforcing all the stipulations therein. Additionally, he must always coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer to keep abreast of water disconnections and to act on it accordingly;
The Municipal Treasurer should impose the 20% interest/penalty beginning January, 2023 onwards to all unpaid bills including arrears, for some, of the consumers including:
a. Compute the corresponding penalties for the current and those long-time arrears, for some, and include them as part of the outstanding liabilities of the consumers to be collected;
b. Present and submit a copy of the Aging of Receivables relative thereto to the Office of the Auditor;
c. Prepare and send a demand/collection letter address to the delinquent consumers which will also serve as Notice of Disconnection with due date and furnish the Office of the Auditor with each received copy; and
d. Devise other effective strategies and techniques to expedite the collection of the ₱ 734,383.33 plus the 20% interest/penalty of ₱ 146,876.66, approximately.
The Kadingilan Water District Supervisor should strictly implement all the stipulations in the water service contract especially when there is already a breach with its terms and conditions.

We recommended to the management to do the following courses of action:

To immediately submit the appropriation ordinance for the foregoing disbursements to the Office of the Auditor for review and verification;
To instantly submit all the financial reports, records and the like of the Municipal Food Terminal that tackle the inflow and outflow of fund/money since its inception last May 9, 2017 to COA for audit;
To directly submit an inventory report of the of the two-hundred fifty two (252) sacks of rice and directly record the remaining sacks as inventories particularly under the account “Inventory Held for Sale” and the sold sacks under the “Cost of Sales” account for the current year and “Prior Period Adjustments” for the previous year duly supported with complete documentary requirements and working papers and submit them to COA for validation; and
To ensure the complete submission of the supporting documents if procured through public bidding together with the paid disbursement voucher per Section 9.1 of COA Circular 2012-001.

We recommended to the Management to direct:
Instruct the BAC Secretariat to submit a copy of the Mayor’s/Business Permit and Income Tax Returns. For future negotiated procurement (emergency cases), ensure compliance with the required Omnibus Sworn Statement before award;
Submit the necessary supporting documents (e.g.  delivery receipt);
Instruct the canvasser to inform the bidders to supply the necessary details in the RFQs;
Instruct the BAC Secretariat to keep the supplied necessary details of the items disclosed in the Purchase Orders/Contracts;
Instruct the Municipal Property Office to keep the supplied necessary details of the items disclosed in the Inspection and Acceptance Report;
Instruct the concerned office/s to submit the utilization/distribution of the goods procured and received by the agency.

